A 2,192x Valuation

At the moment, DJT=E2=80=99s equity is valued at roughly $6.3 billion, mean=
ing Trump=E2=80=99s 60 percent stake is worth around $3.8 billion. But, as =
is well known by now, that preposterous valuation=E2=80=94about the size of=
 Bausch & Lomb or Alaska Airlines=E2=80=94is not based on economic fundamen=
tals. In the first nine months of 2024, DJT generated a mere $2.6 million i=
n revenue (not a typo) and generated losses of $363 million. That kind of f=
inancial performance is pretty hard to fathom. When you somehow try to reco=
ncile that income statement with the $6.3 billion valuation, you=E2=80=99ve=
 entered the land of the absurd. DJT released third-quarter earnings on Ele=
ction Day, with C.E.O. Devin Nunes, the former California congressman, decl=
aring, =E2=80=9CThis has been an extraordinary quarter for the company.=E2=
=80=9D Thanks, Devin, that=E2=80=99s nice to hear. But Nunes did not
offer any insight on a business model that makes no economic sense or a com=
pany that trades at an incoherent, batshit crazy 2,192x revenue.

The only bright spot at DJT is that the company has no debt, and cash on ha=
nd of $673 million. Since there is no debt, there=E2=80=99s no immediate th=
reat of bankruptcy, which would distinguish DJT from Trump=E2=80=99s other =
public and private companies, six of which filed for bankruptcy because of =
debt burdens that could not be repaid. (Others, such as Trump University an=
d Trump Steaks, simply shut down.)

Then there=E2=80=99s X. You=E2=80=99ll recall that Musk paid $44 billion fo=
r Twitter two years ago by raising $31 billion of equity=E2=80=94some $24 b=
illion of his own cash, plus funds from friends and family including Larry =
Ellison ($1 billion) and Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Prince Alwaleed, who rolled=
 over his $1.9 billion of Twitter winnings into Elon=E2=80=99s X=E2=80=94an=
d borrowing the other $13 billion from a group of Wall Street
banks, led by Morgan Stanley and Bank of America.

X is now a private company, so information regarding its financial performa=
nce is hard to come by and is necessarily of the leaked variety, and thus n=
eeds to be taken with a whole brick of salt. But according to =E2=80=9Cinte=
rnal documents=E2=80=9D obtained by Bloomberg, X is expected to generate ne=
arly $3 billion in revenue in 2024, most of it from ad sales, down from $3.=
4 billion in 2023 and $4.4 billion in 2022. Andrew Hutchinson, writing in S=
ocial Media Today, predicts that with annual interest expenses of $1.2 bill=
ion on the $13 billion of debt, X =E2=80=9Clooks set to post a significant =
loss in 2024, which could even result in bankruptcy for the former bird app=
=2E=E2=80=9D In fact, if Musk, with a fort=
une these days of an astounding $31=
9 billion=E2=80=94an increase of $90 billion so far in 2024 alone=E2=80=94w=
eren=E2=80=99t making those $1.2 billion in annual interest payments, most =
of which is probably coming out of his own pocket,
Twitter/X would likely have filed for bankruptcy long ago.

Is there any equity value in X? I have long argued that the equity value of=
 X has evaporated and that its $13 billion of debt would probably trade aro=
und 50 cents on the dollar. But as best as I can tell, none of that debt ha=
s been sold, although some of the banks have likely taken their writedowns =
while keeping those marks very quiet. Wall Street banks like to say they=E2=
=80=99re in the moving business, not the storage business, and they need to=
 get that X sludge off their balance sheets, even though the interest payme=
nts are current thanks to Elon=E2=80=99s ongoing largesse.

Some of X=E2=80=99s equity investors, though, are starting to face the real=
ity that their investment in the company is close to worthless. Fidelity, f=
or one, has marked down its equity investment by 80 percent. That=E2=80=99s=
 still generous, but directionally correct, at least.

