          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">At the moment, DJT=
=E2=80=99s equity is valued at roughly $6.3 billion, meaning Trump=E2=80=99=
s 60 percent stake is worth around $3.8 billion. But, as is well known by n=
ow, that preposterous valuation=E2=80=94about the size of Bausch &amp; Lomb=
 or Alaska Airlines=E2=80=94is not based on economic fundamentals. In the f=
irst nine months of 2024, DJT generated a mere $2.6 million in revenue (not=
 a typo) and generated losses of $363 million. That kind of financial perfo=
rmance is pretty hard to fathom. When you somehow try to reconcile that inc=
ome statement with the $6.3 billion valuation, you=E2=80=99ve entered the l=
and of the absurd. DJT released third-quarter earnings on Election Day, wit=
h C.E.O. <b>Devin</b> <b>Nunes</b>, the former California congressman, decl=
aring, =E2=80=9CThis has been an extraordinary quarter for the company.=E2=
=80=9D Thanks, Devin, that=E2=80=99s nice to hear. But Nunes did not
offer any insight on a business model that makes no economic sense or a com=
pany that trades at an incoherent, batshit crazy <i>2,192x</i> revenue. <br=
/><br/>The only bright spot at DJT is that the company has no debt, and cas=
h on hand of $673 million. Since there is no debt, there=E2=80=99s no immed=
iate threat of bankruptcy, which would distinguish DJT from Trump=E2=80=99s=
 other public and private companies, six of which filed for bankruptcy beca=
use of debt burdens that could not be repaid. (Others, such as Trump Univer=
sity and Trump Steaks, simply shut down.) <br/><br/>Then there=E2=80=99s X.=
 You=E2=80=99ll recall that Musk paid $44 billion for Twitter two years ago=
 by raising $31 billion of equity=E2=80=94some $24 billion of his own cash,=
 plus funds from friends and family including <b>Larry Ellison </b>($1 bill=
ion) and Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s <b>Prince</b> <b>Alwaleed</b>, who rolled o=
ver his $1.9 billion of Twitter winnings into Elon=E2=80=99s X=E2=80=94and =
borrowing the other $13 billion from a group of Wall Street
banks, led by Morgan Stanley and Bank of America. <br/><br/>X is now a priv=
ate company, so information regarding its financial performance is hard to =
come by and is necessarily of the leaked variety, and thus needs to be take=
n with a whole brick of salt. But according to =E2=80=9Cinternal documents=
=E2=80=9D obtained by Bloomberg, X is expected to generate nearly $3 billio=
n in revenue in 2024, most of it from ad sales, down from $3.4 billion in 2=
023 and $4.4 billion in 2022. <b>Andrew</b> <b>Hutchinson</b>, writing in S=
ocial Media Today, predicts that with annual interest expenses of $1.2 bill=
ion on the $13 billion of debt, X =E2=80=9Clooks set to post a significant =
loss in 2024, which could even result in bankruptcy for the former bird app=
=2E=E2=80=9D In fact, if Musk, with a fort=
une these days of an astounding <i>=
$319 billion</i>=E2=80=94an increase of $90 billion so far in 2024 alone=E2=
=80=94weren=E2=80=99t making those $1.2 billion in annual interest payments=
, most of which is probably coming out of his own pocket,
Twitter/X would likely have filed for bankruptcy long ago. <br/><br/>Is the=
re any equity value in X? I have long argued that the equity value of X has=
 evaporated and that its $13 billion of debt would probably trade around 50=
 cents on the dollar. But as best as I can tell, none of that debt has been=
 sold, although some of the banks have likely taken their writedowns while =
keeping those marks very quiet. Wall Street banks like to say they=E2=80=99=
re in the <i>moving</i> <i>business</i>, not the <i>storage</i> <i>business=
</i>, and they need to get that X sludge off their balance sheets, even tho=
ugh the interest payments are current thanks to Elon=E2=80=99s ongoing larg=
esse. <br/><br/>Some of X=E2=80=99s equity investors, though, are starting =
to face the reality that their investment in the company is close to worthl=
ess. Fidelity, for one, has marked down its equity investment by 80 percent=
=2E That=E2=80=99s still generous, but dir=
ectionally correct, at least.<br/><=
/td>
